# Preprocessing of files
class Preprocessing:
    def __init__(self, test_img, threshold, radius, l, t, r, b):
        self.test_img = test_img  # generic image file
        self.threshold = threshold  # the amout of dBZ that when exceeded will label image as wet
        self.radius = radius  # radius of center circle that we are predicting weather for
        self.color_mapping = {}  # maps pixel value to dBZ value
        self.init_color_map()
        self.dbz_sums = []  # the total dbZ value of an image (when looking at center circle)
        # left, right, top, bottom pixel coordinates
        self.l = l
        self.t = t
        self.r = r
        self.b = b
        assert b - t == r - l, "images must be cropped to a square"
        self.size = b - t
        # gets the coordinates of the pixels in the center of the map (used for labeling the image)
        self.xs, self.ys = self.get_circle_pixels()
        
    # mapping of pixel value to dBZ value (just initializes them all at 0 for now)
    def init_color_map(self):
        keys = np.arange(101)
        for key in keys:
            self.color_mapping[key] = 0
        self.get_color_values()
        
    # updates color mapping dictionary, mapping color values to dbz value 
    #(how much precipitation is represented by each color)
    def get_color_values(self):
        tes = 0
        x = 400
        y = 160
        self.colors = []
        color_weights = [60, 57.5, 55, 52.5, 50, 47.5, 45, 42.5, 40, 36.5, 33, 28, 23, 7]
        
        for y in range (150, 400, 5):
            color = self.test_img.getpixel((520, y))
            if color == 0:
                break
            if color not in self.colors:
                self.colors.append(color)

        for (c, w) in zip(self.colors, color_weights):
            self.color_mapping[c] = w

    # crops image    
    def crop(self, img):
        return img.crop((self.l, self.t, self.r, self.b))
    
    # gets the y coordinates corresponding to every x in the circle (using eqn for a circle)
    def iterate_over_circle(self, xs):
        ys = []
        for i in range(xs.shape[0]):
            perimeter = int(round((self.radius * self.radius - xs[i] * xs[i]) ** (1/2)))
            count = 0
            y = np.zeros(2 * perimeter + 1)
            for j in range(-perimeter, perimeter + 1):
                y[count] = j
                count += 1
            ys.append(y)
        return ys
    
    # shifts the coordinates of the circle so it is centered in the image
    def recenter(self, xs, ys):
        # double check this
        xs += self.size // 2
        for y in ys:
            y += self.size // 2
        return xs, ys
    
    # gets the weighted sum of the pixels in the center most circle
    def get_pixel_vals(self, img):
        dbz_sum = 0
        for (x, y) in zip(self.xs, self.ys):
            for ind in range(y.shape[0]):
                pix = img.getpixel((x, int(y[ind]))) # gets the pixel value
                dbz_sum += self.color_mapping[pix]
        return dbz_sum
    
    # returns a two lists that together contain all coordinates of the circle
    def get_circle_pixels(self):
        xs = np.arange(81) - 40
        ys = self.iterate_over_circle(xs)
        xs, ys = self.recenter(xs, ys)
        return xs, ys
    
    # returns 0 or 1 for all images if the center radius meets pixel threshold
    def get_label(self, img):
        img = self.crop(img)
        dbz_sum = self.get_pixel_vals(img)
        self.dbz_sums.append(dbz_sum)
        return int(dbz_sum >= self.threshold), img

# for managing file names (time stamps)
class File:
    def __init__(self, start, end, file_loc):
        self.file_names = []
        self.file_loc = file_loc
        self.generate_file_names(start, end)
        
    # makes file names given start and end dates
    def generate_file_names(self, start, end):
        timestamp = start
        self.file_names = [self.file_loc + datetime.datetime.strftime(start, "%Y%m%d%H%M") + ".gif"]
        while (timestamp != end):
            timestamp += datetime.timedelta(minutes=10)
            self.file_names.append(self.file_loc + datetime.datetime.strftime(timestamp, "%Y%m%d%H%M") + ".gif")

# can load file for X and Y if you have previously saved
# warning - will take substantial amount of time to run
def make_X_and_Y(files):
    Y = np.zeros(len(files)) # labels
    X = [] # inputs
    i = 0
    max_dbz = 60
    # actually applies pixel value to dBZ value here and then scales
    scale = np.vectorize(lambda x: 0.0 if x not in preprocessor.colors else preprocessor.color_mapping[x] / max_dbz)
    for file_name in files:
        try:
            img = PIL.Image.open(file_name)
            Y[i], img = preprocessor.get_label(img)
            arr = np.asarray(img)
            rescaled = scale(arr)
            reshaped = tf.reshape(rescaled, (1, preprocessor.size, preprocessor.size, 1))

            # change reduction here, avg pool used - 16 to 1
            reduced = tf.nn.avg_pool(reshaped, ksize=4, strides=4, padding="SAME") 
            to_append = np.array(tf.squeeze(reduced))
            X.append(to_append)
        
        # for corrupt files...
        except FileNotFoundError:
            Y[i] = np.nan
            X.append(np.nan)
            preprocessor.dbz_sums.append(np.nan)

        except PIL.UnidentifiedImageError:
            Y[i] = np.nan
            X.append(np.nan)
            preprocessor.dbz_sums.append(np.nan)

        # for output progress
        if i % 1000 == 0:
            print("{0:.1%}".format(i / len(files)))
        i += 1
    print("DONE")
    return X, Y

X, Y = make_X_and_Y(files)

# choose 49 randomly labeled images and see if they are labeled right...
def display_images(files, num_images):
    rand = list(np.round(np.random.rand(num_images) * len(files)))
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10), dpi=200)
    subplot_num = 1
    for i in rand:
        file_name = files[int(i)]
        plt.subplot(7, 7, subplot_num)
        plt.xticks([])
        plt.yticks([])
        plt.grid(False)
        # attempts to open image, if unable to opens a default one instead
        try:
            img = PIL.Image.open(file_name)
            img = img.crop((195, 195, 285, 285))
            # labels the image as wet or dry and also shows the dBZ value
            plt.xlabel("Y: " + str(round(Y[int(i)])) + \
                       ". dBZ: " + str(round(preprocessor.dbz_sums[int(i)])))
        except:
            print("Warning one image not loaded - substituting with test image")
            img = PIL.Image.open(file_loc + "201804010300.gif")
            img = img.crop((195, 195, 285, 285))
            plt.xlabel("test image")

        plt.imshow(img)
        img.close()

        subplot_num += 1
    plt.show()

# generates the windows
def gen_windows(x_win, y_win, freq):
    indices = [] # used to group the indices together in windows of x_win + y_win
    tot_win = x_win + y_win 
    for m in range(freq):
        for i in range(m, int(Y.shape[0] / freq) - tot_win, 1):
            window = np.zeros(tot_win, np.int16)
            flag = False
            for l in range(tot_win):
                timestep = int((i + l) * freq + m)
                if Y[timestep] == 1 or Y[timestep] == 0:
                    window[l] = timestep
                else:
                    # given there is corrupted/ missing data
                    # remove all samples in the same window
                    flag = True
                    break

            if not flag:
                indices.append(window)
    return indices

freq = 1  # whether to skip images (predict every 10 min = 1, every 20 min = 2, etc...)
x_win = 24 # how many inputs at freq above (24 10 min inputs)
y_win = 24 # how many predictions at freq above (24 10 min predictions)
indices = gen_windows(x_win, y_win, freq)

# lets just use longest two sequences 
num_seq = 2

def split_data(indices, start, stop):
    train_split = round((stop - start) * .8) + start
    val_split = round((stop - start) * .9) + start
    train = []
    val = []
    test = []
    
    for arr in indices:
        if arr[0] >= start and arr[0] < train_split:
            train.append(arr)
        elif arr[0] >= train_split and arr[0] < val_split:
            val.append(arr)
        elif arr[0] >= val_split and arr[0] <= stop:
            test.append(arr)
    return train, val, test

# note that the lists above have their input and output joined together
# so we need to grab the image vectors for the x_win length (to be used as input)
# and then take the remaining indices (y_win) and get their labels from Y

# makes datasets
class Dataset:
    def __init__(self, name, indices, x_win, y_win, num_feat, num_add_dim):
        self.name = name
        self.indices = indices
        self.num_samples = len(indices)
        self.x_win = x_win
        self.y_win = y_win
        self.tot_win = self.x_win + self.y_win
        self.num_feat = num_feat
        self.num_add_dim = num_add_dim
        self.ins = np.zeros((self.num_samples, x_win, self.num_feat), dtype=np.float32)
        self.outs = np.zeros((self.num_samples, y_win), dtype=np.int8)
        
    # makes input and output     
    def separate_in_from_out(self, X, Y):
        print("================== " + self.name + " ========================")
        for i in range(self.num_samples):
            for j in range(self.tot_win):
                index_num = self.indices[i][j]
                if j < self.x_win:
                    self.ins[i][j] = (X[index_num]).flatten() # images as input (after vectorization)
                else:
                    self.outs[i][j - x_win] = Y[index_num]  # the labels
            if i % 800 == 0:
                print("{0:.1%}".format(i / self.num_samples))
        # based on model architecture we need input in different shapes...
        if num_add_dim == 1:
            self.ins = np.reshape(self.ins, (self.num_samples, self.x_win, self.num_feat, 1))
        elif num_add_dim == 2:
            self.ins = np.reshape(self.ins, (self.num_samples, self.x_win, round(math.sqrt(self.num_feat)), round(math.sqrt(self.num_feat)), 1))
        print("Complete")
    
    
# 0 for no conv lstm, 1 for 1d conv lstm, 2 for 2d conv lstm
num_add_dim = 0
datasets = {} # stores all data with key being the data name (train, val, test...)
for name in names:
    datasets[name] = Dataset(name, split_indices[name], x_win, y_win, X[0].size, num_add_dim)
    datasets[name].separate_in_from_out(X, Y)
    
print("Your input shape will be... ", datasets["train"].ins.shape)

# base model - simply guess last label
def base_model_predictions(indices, Y, x_win):
    predictions = []
    count = 0
    correct = 0
    predictions = []
    # indices are 48 element arrays of indexes, first 24 for input, next 24 for label output
    for ind in indices: 
        pred = [Y[ind[x_win - 1]]] * (len(ind) - x_win)
        predictions += pred
        for i in range(x_win, len(ind)):
            count += 1
            ac = Y[ind[i]]
            if ac == pred[0]:
                correct += 1
    return correct, count, np.array(predictions)

# shows baseline model results
def print_base_model_pred(truths, truths2, ind, ind2, to_print):    
    correct, count, predictions = base_model_predictions(ind, Y, x_win)
    correct2, count2, predictions2 = base_model_predictions(ind2, Y, x_win)

    acc = (correct / count)
    acc2 = (correct2 / count2)
    accuracy = (correct + correct2) / (count + count2)
    print(to_print)
    print(sklearn.metrics.classification_report(truths, predictions))
    print(sklearn.metrics.classification_report(truths2, predictions2))
    print("Accuracy 1: {0:.1%}\nAccuracy 2: {1:.1%}".format(acc, acc2))
    return predictions, predictions2

# taking the label of the 4th hour and predicting 4 more hours with that baseline...

# confusion matrix
def display_conf_mat(truths, preds, name, i=None, axes=None):
    conf_mat = np.array(sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix(truths, preds))
    if i != None:
        ax = sns.heatmap(conf_mat, annot=True, center=5000, ax=axes[i // 2, i % 2])
    else:
        ax = sns.heatmap(conf_mat, annot=True, center=5000)
        
    ax = ax.set(xlabel="Predicted", ylabel="Actual", title=name)

# Our model...
# batch size and dropouts
batch_size = 64
rdrop = .4 # recurrent
drop = .8
drop2 = .5
drop3 = .5

#metric = "binary_accuracy"
#metric = tf.keras.metrics.AUC()
metric = tf.keras.metrics.SensitivityAtSpecificity(.5, name="tpr/tnr") # to make sure we dont just predict all 0's
opt = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam()
num_feat = X[0].size 

#loss = tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy() 
loss = tf.keras.losses.poisson # to help put more emphasis on negative class (due to class imbalance)

# callbacks
reduce_lr = tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(patience=3, monitor="val_tpr/tnr", mode="max")
early_stop = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(patience=5, monitor="val_tpr/tnr", mode="max", restore_best_weights=True)
val_reduce_lr = tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(patience=3, monitor=str("tpr/tnr"), mode="max")
val_early_stop = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(patience=5, monitor=str("tpr/tnr"), mode="max", restore_best_weights=True)
callbacks = [reduce_lr, early_stop]
val_callbacks = [val_reduce_lr, val_early_stop]

# building the model
model = tf.keras.Sequential()
model.add(tf.keras.layers.SimpleRNN(512, input_shape=(x_win, num_feat), \
                                    return_sequences=True, recurrent_dropout=rdrop)) # .4
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(drop)) # .8
model.add(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(24, input_shape=(x_win, num_feat), \
                               return_sequences=False, recurrent_dropout=rdrop)) # .4
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(drop2)) # .5
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Flatten())
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(48, activation="relu"))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(drop3)) # .5
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(x_win, activation="sigmoid"))
# compile
model.compile(opt, loss,  metrics=[metric, "binary_accuracy"])

# Makes sample weights
def gen_sample_weights(sample_weights, name, factor, outs, x_win):
    length = outs.shape[0]
    sample_weights[name] = np.zeros(length)
    for i in range(length):
        # puts more weight on samples with more than 2/3rds of their labels are 1's
        sample_weights[name][i] = int(np.mean(outs[i]) > .66) * factor + 1 
    return sample_weights

# Predictions
def print_pred(data, name, batch_size):
    truths = data.outs.flatten()
    preds = np.round(model.predict(data.ins, batch_size=batch_size)).flatten()
    print(name)
    print(sklearn.metrics.classification_report(truths, preds))
    return truths, preds

truths, preds = print_pred(datasets["val"], "val", batch_size)

# Plots training curve
def make_training_curve(history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 3))
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
    plt.plot(history.history["loss"], label="train")
    plt.plot(history.history["val_loss"], label="val")
    plt.ylabel("Poisson Loss")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.legend()

    plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
    plt.plot(history.history["binary_accuracy"], label="train")
    plt.plot(history.history["val_binary_accuracy"], label="val")
    plt.ylabel("Binary Accuracy")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    
    
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
    plt.plot(history.history["tpr/tnr"], label="train")
    plt.plot(history.history["val_tpr/tnr"], label="val")
    plt.ylabel("Sensitivity at specificity=.5")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    

make_training_curve(history)

def use_val_to_train(model, name):
    print(name)
    val_history = model.fit(x=datasets[name].ins, y=datasets[name].outs, batch_size=batch_size, epochs=5, \
                    shuffle=False, validation_data=None, callbacks=val_callbacks)
    return val_history

# Plots training on validation data
def plot_training_on_val(val_history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 3))
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
    plt.plot(val_history.history["loss"], label="val")
    plt.ylabel("Poisson Loss")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.legend()
    
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
    plt.plot(val_history.history["binary_accuracy"], label="val")
    plt.ylabel("Binary Accuracy")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.legend()
    
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
    plt.plot(val_history.history["tpr/tnr"], label="val")
    plt.ylabel("Sensitivity at specificity=.5")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
plot_training_on_val(val_history)
